The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Global cues boost market sentiment
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Global cues boost market sentiment
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                                             
	Mumbai, Feb. 3: The BSE sensex today surged nearly 333 points, helped by firm global trends, with banks, realty and metal stocks leading the rally.         
	The 30-share benchmark index closed at 16496.05, up 2.06 per cent, after it opened on a positive note at 16210.25 and reached a high of 16552.99.         
	Better-than-expected earnings by the US companies led to a rally in the global markets, providing investors a good base for trading.        
	The Asian indices such as Hang Seng, Nikkei, Shanghai Composite, Strait Times, Kospi and Taiwan weighted index rose in the range of 0.32 per cent to 2.36 per cent today.         
	European stocks were also trading higher in the morning.         
	According to brokers, short-covering also helped the market to close on a strong note. The broader 50-issue Nifty of the National Stock Exchange also rose 101.75 points, or 2.11 per cent, to close at 4931.85.         
	Metal stocks scored huge gains because of a rally in commodity prices and positive sentiment in the US.         
	Sterlite Industries, which rose 5.97 per cent, moved up the most, followed by Tata Steel, which was up 4.91 per cent. Other gainers included JSW Steel and Hindalco Industries.         
	L amp;T shares jumped 3.80 per cent on the news of the company receiving more orders.         
	The HDFC scrip gained 3.76 per cent, ICICI Bank, 2.56 per cent, and HDFC Bank, 2.19 per cent.         
	Among the BSE sectoral indices, metals rise of 640.09 points, or 4.01 per cent, was the highest followed by realty, which was up 96.75 points, or 2.81 per cent.         
	The capital goods index surged 275.18 points, or 2.12 per cent, and the bankex, 195.53 points, or 2.07 per cent.                                                                                                                                      
